ggory Nations]]\n |Aux2=[[Miles Straume|Miles]]\n |Viewers=9.23<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/04/21/top-abc-primetime-shows-april-13-19-2009/17135/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, April 13\u201319, 2009 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |author=Seidman, Robert |date=April 21, 2009 |accessdate=April 21, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503101701/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/04/21/top-abc-primetime-shows-april-13-19-2009/17135/ |archivedate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=In 1977, Roger, Ben's father, begins to suspect Kate in Ben's disappearance. Miles is given the task of taking a body from the construction site of the Swan Station, to his father, Dr. Chang. In flashbacks, Miles learns of his ability to speak with the dead and is hired to travel to the island on the freighter.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Lost (season 5)\n |EpisodeNumber=100\n |EpisodeNumber2=14\n |Title=[[The Variable]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2009|4|29}}\n |DirectedBy=Paul Edwards\n |WrittenBy=Edward Kitsis & Adam Horowitz\n |Aux2=[[Daniel Faraday|Faraday]]\n |Viewers=9.04<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/06/top-abc-primetime-shows-april-27-may-3-2009/18170/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, April 27 - May 3, 2009 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |author=Seidman, Robert |date=May 6, 2009 |accessdate=May 6, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503101706/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/06/top-abc-primetime-shows-april-27-may-3-2009/18170/ |archivedate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=In 1977, Daniel Faraday returns to the island in order to warn its inhabitants of a catastrophe involving the Swan Station. Jack, Kate, and Daniel start a gun fight with the Dharma Initiative, leading Dharma to go after Sawyer and Juliet. Daniel has a plan to change the future by detonating the hydrogen bomb at the same time as the Incident at the Swan Station. However, when he goes to the others to find out where the bomb is, he is shot in the back and killed by the younger version of his own mother. In flashbacks, Daniel's relationship with his parents, Eloise Hawking and Charles Widmore, is shown.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Lost (season 5)\n |EpisodeNumber=101\n |EpisodeNumber2=15\n |Title=[[Follow the Leader (Lost)|Follow the Leader]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2009|5|6}}\n |DirectedBy=Stephen Williams\n |WrittenBy=Paul Zbyszewski & Elizabeth Sarnoff\n |Aux2=''none''\n |Viewers=8.70<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/12/top-abc-primetime-shows-may-4-10-2009/18547/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, May 4\u201310, 2009 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |author=Seidman, Robert |date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=May 12, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503101730/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/12/top-abc-primetime-shows-may-4-10-2009/18547/ |archivedate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=In 1977, Jack decides to follow Faraday's advice to detonate the hydrogen bomb, however Kate disagrees. Dr. Chang convinces Dharma to evacuate the island, allowing Sawyer, Kate and Juliet to board the submarine and leave the island. In 2007, Locke reunites with the Others and Richard, who accompany him on a journey to kill Jacob.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Lost (season 5)\n |EpisodeNumber=102<hr />103\n |EpisodeNumber2=16<hr />17\n |Title=[[The Incident (Lost)|The Incident]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2009|5|13}}\n |DirectedBy=Jack Bender\n |WrittenBy=Damon Lindelof & Carlton Cuse\n |Aux2=[[Jacob (Lost)|Jacob]]\n |Viewers=9.43<ref name=\"Season 5 finale ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/19/top-abc-primetime-shows-may-11-17-2009/19083/ |title=Top ABC Primetime Shows, May 11\u201317, 2009 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |author=Seidman, Robert |date=May 19, 2009 |accessdate=May 19, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503101747/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/19/top-abc-primetime-shows-may-11-17-2009/19083/ |archivedate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=In 1977, the survivors succeed in detonating the modified nuclear bomb at the construction site of the Swan station, the finale ending when the bomb is detonated. In 2007, Locke and the Others travel to the base of the four-toed statue, where Jacob lives. Locke is revealed to be an impostor: an old acquaintance of Jacob who manipulates Ben into killing Jacob. In flashbacks, Jacob visits several of the main characters at key moments in their lives prior to crashing on the island.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}\n }}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Home media release==\nThe DVD and Blu-ray box set of season 5 was released on December 8, 2009, in Region 1,<ref name=\"s5 dvd\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Lost-Season-5/11652 |title=Lost - Disney Officially Announces 'The Complete 5th Season' on Blu-ray & DVD |publisher=TVShowsOnDVD |author=Lambert, David |date=April 8, 2009 |accessdate=April 15, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411041722/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Lost-Season-5/11652 |archivedate=April 11, 2009 }}</ref> on October 21, 2009, in Region 4, and on October 26, 2009, in Region 2. It includes all episodes in the season and bonus features including:\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 1em 0 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#69D0E3\"\n| colspan=\"6\" | <span style=\"color:black;\">'''''Lost: The Complete Fifth Season \u2013 The Journey Back, Expanded Edition'''''</span>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\" width=\"400\" colspan=\"3\"| '''Set details'''\n| width=\"400\" align=\"center\" colspan=\"3\"|'''Special features'''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|\n* 17 episodes\n* 5-disc set\n* 1.78:1 aspect ratio\n* Subtitles: English, Spanish, French\n* English (Dolby Digital 5.1 Surround) \u2013 DVD\n* English (DTS-HD Master Audio 5.1 Surround) \u2013 Blu-ray\n\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\" width=\"400\"|\n* Audio commentaries\n** \"Because You Left\" by Damon Lindelof and Carlton Cuse\n** \"He's Our You\" by Edward Kitsis and Adam Horowitz\n* \"Lost on Location\"\n* \"Building 23 & Beyond\"\n* \"An Epic Day with Richard Alpert\"\n* \"Making Up for Lost Time\"\n* \"Mysteries of the Universe: The DHARMA Initiative\"\n* \"Bloopers\"\n* \"Deleted Scenes\"\n* \"Lost Starter Kit\"\n*Blu-ray exclusive\n** \"Lost 100\"\n** \"Lost University\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | '''Release dates'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | {{USA}}<br />{{CAN}}\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | {{AUS}}\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | {{UK}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | December 8, 2009\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | October 21, 2009\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | October 26, 2009\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*List of [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0411008/episodes?season=5 ''Lost'' season 5 episodes] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*List of [http://lostpedia.wikia.com/wiki/Season_5 ''Lost'' season 5 episodes] at [[Lostpedia]]\n\n{{Lost (TV series)}}\n{{Lost episodes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lost (Season 5)}}\n[[Category:Lost (TV series)]]\n[[Category:2009 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:Lost (season 5) episodes| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Season of television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox television season\n|season_number    = 5\n|bgcolor          = #69D0E3\n|image            = Lost S5 DVD.jpg\n|image_upright    = 1.15\n|caption          = DVD cover\n| starring         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Naveen Andrews]]\n* [[Henry Ian Cusick]]\n* [[Jeremy Davies]]\n* [[Michael Emerson]]\n* [[Matthew Fox]]\n* [[Jorge Garcia]]\n* [[Josh Holloway]]\n* [[Daniel Dae Kim]]\n* [[Yunjin Kim]]\n* [[Ken Leung]]\n* [[Evangeline Lilly]]\n* [[Rebecca Mader]]\n* [[Elizabeth Mitchell]]\n* [[Terry O'Quinn]]\n}}\n|country          = United States\n|network          = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n|first_aired      = {{Start date|2009|1|21}}\n|last_aired       = {{End date|2009|5|13}}\n|num_episodes     = 17\n|prev_season      = [[Lost (season 4)|Season 4]]\n|next_season      = [[Lost (season 6)|Season 6]]\n|episode_list     = List of Lost episodes\n}}\n\nThe fifth season of the American [[Serial (radio and television)|serial drama]] [[Television program|television series]] ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' commenced airing on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network in the United States and on [[A (TV system)|A]] in Canada in January 2009, and concluded with a two-hour season finale on May 13, 2009.<ref>{{cite press|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=031609_01 |title=ABC Announces Finale Dates Plus Two Returns |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate=March 16, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326084944/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=031609_01 |archivedate=March 26, 2009 }}</ref> The [[Television program#Seasons.2Fseries|season]] continues the stories of the survivors of the fictional crash of [[Oceanic Airlines]] Flight 815, after some of them are rescued and those still stranded seemingly disappear to an unknown location and time with the island that they inhabit.\n\nAccording to ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''{{'s}} co-creator/executive producer/writer/[[show runner]] [[Damon Lindelof]], the season \"is about why [the people who have left the island] need to get back\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Albiniak, Paige |date=February 24, 2008 |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/02242008/tv/10_reasons_why_lost_is_found_98856.htm |title=Ten Reasons Why ''Lost'' is Found |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=March 17, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080229004444/http://www.nypost.com/seven/02242008/tv/10_reasons_why_lost_is_found_98856.htm |archivedate=February 29, 2008 }}</ref> ''Lost'' returned on January 21, 2009, on ABC with a three-hour premiere consisting of a [[clip-show]] and two back-to-back new episodes. The remainder of the season aired on Wednesdays at 9:00 pm EST.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jensen, Jeff |date=November 7, 2008 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/11/07/losts-fifth-sea/ |title=''Lost'' Season 5 Gets a Premiere Date |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=November 7, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815215831/http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/11/07/losts-fifth-sea/ |archivedate=August 15, 2011 }}</ref> The season began in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] on January 25, 2009, on [[Sky1]] and [[RT\u00c9 Two]], respectively. The season was released on DVD and Blu-ray Disc under the title ''Lost: The Complete Fifth Season \u2013 The Journey Back, Expanded Edition'' on December 8, 2009.<ref name=\"s5 dvd\"/>\n\n==Crew==\nThe season was produced by [[Bad Robot Productions]] and Grass Skirt Productions and was aired on the [[American Broadcasting Company]] network in the United States.<ref>{{cite press|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=March 21, 2007 |url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=032107_03 |title=Fourteen Early Pick-Ups Announced for the 2007\u201308 Season |accessdate=July 7, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103043527/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=032107_03 |archivedate=January 3, 2009 }}</ref> The show was primarily filmed in [[Hawaii]] with [[post-production]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brislin, Tom |date=January 25, 2007 |url=http://www.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=1664 |title=UH Academy for Creative Media, ''Lost'', Create Student Internship Program |publisher=[[University of Hawaii]] |accessdate=August 30, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918081938/http://hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=1664 |archivedate=September 18, 2009 }}</ref> Damon Lindelof and [[Carlton Cuse]] continued to serve as the show runners.<ref>{{cite web|author=Keller, Joel |date=January 15, 2007 |url=http://www.aoltv.com/2007/01/15/abcs-show-runners-talk-about-pitching-network-notes-and-inter |title=ABC's Show Runners Talk About Pitching, Network Notes, and Internet Scrutiny |publisher=Aol TV |accessdate=August 30, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905141712/http://www.aoltv.com/2007/01/15/abcs-show-runners-talk-about-pitching-network-notes-and-inter |archivedate=September 5, 2012 }}</ref> Lindelof and Cuse's fellow executive producers were co-creator [[J. J. Abrams]], [[Bryan Burk]], [[Jack Bender]], [[Edward Kitsis]] and [[Adam Horowitz (screenwriter)|Adam Horowitz]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Frutkin, A.J. |date=March 1, 2007 |url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/networktv/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003552276&imw=Y |title=ABC Signs ''Lost''{{'s}} Kitsis, Horowitz to Three-Year Deal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209015213/http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/networktv/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003552276&imw=Y |archivedate=February 9, 2008 |work=[[MediaWeek]] |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The staff writers were Lindelof, Cuse, Kitsis, Horowitz, co-executive producer [[Elizabeth Sarnoff]], supervising producer [[Paul Zbyszewski]], producer [[Brian K. Vaughan]], co-producer Melinda Hsu Taylor and [[Kyle Pennington]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Bennett, Tara |date=October 14, 2008 |title=Tales From the Freighter: New Transmissions \u2013 Unearthed Treasures |journal=Lost: The Official Magazine |publisher=[[Titan Magazines]] |issue=19}}</ref> The regular directors are Bender, co-executive producer [[Stephen Williams (director)|Stephen Williams]] and [[Paul A. Edwards|Paul Edwards]].\n\n==Cast==\nThe [[Characters of Lost|cast]] features 14 major roles with [[Billing (film)|star billing]], all of whom return from the [[Lost (season 4)|fourth season]]. Because the storyline follows two different time periods, the cast is largely broken into two groups. The first storyline follows the group of people who have left the island: the survivors' leader Dr. [[Jack Shephard]] ([[Matthew Fox (actor)|Matthew Fox]]), ex-fugitive [[Kate Austen]] ([[Evangeline Lilly]]), mentally unstable millionaire [[Hugo \"Hurley\" Reyes]] ([[Jorge Garcia]]), former torturer [[Sayid Jarrah]] ([[Naveen Andrews]]), grieving wife [[Sun-Hwa Kwon]] ([[Yunjin Kim]]), three-year islander [[Desmond Hume]] ([[Henry Ian Cusick]]) and [[Ben Linus]] ([[Michael Emerson]]), former leader of the island's native population, known as the [[Others (Lost)|Others]]. The second follows those who remain on the island as they erratically jump through time, following the island being moved in the fourth-season finale. They are crash survivor and con man [[James \"Sawyer\" Ford]] ([[Josh Holloway]]), former Other and fertility specialist Dr. [[Juliet Burke]] ([[Elizabeth Mitchell]]), crash survivor and former enforcer [[Jin Kwon]] ([[Daniel Dae Kim]]), who survived the explosion of the freighter,<ref name=\"There's No Place Like Home\">{{cite episode |credits=[[Damon Lindelof|Lindelof, Damon]] (writer), [[Carlton Cuse|Cuse, Carlton]] (writer), [[Jack Bender|Bender, Jack]] (director) |title=[[There's No Place Like Home (Lost)|There's No Place Like Home]] |series=[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]] |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |season=4 |number=13\u201314 |airdate=May 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |credits=[[Brian K. Vaughan|Vaughan, Brian K.]] (writer), Taylor, Melinda Hsu (writer), [[Stephen Williams (director)|Williams, Stephen]] (director) |title=[[The Little Prince (Lost)|The Little Prince]] |series=[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]] |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |season=5 |number=4 |airdate=February 4, 2009}}</ref> and three members of a science team from a freighter offshore, who have joined the crash survivors: [[mediumship|medium]] [[Miles Straume]] ([[Ken Leung]]), anthropologist [[Charlotte Lewis (Lost)|Charlotte Lewis]] ([[Rebecca Mader]]), and physicist [[Daniel Faraday]] ([[Jeremy Davies]]). The only main character to be involved in both storylines is [[John Locke (Lost)|John Locke]] ([[Terry O'Quinn]]), who, at the end of the fourth season, leaves his fellow crash survivors to become the new leader of the Others. However, following the first jump through time, he rejoins the crash survivors and eventually leaves the island and dies, which prompts the other survivors who have left the island to return with his body.<ref name=\"There's No Place Like Home\"/><ref name=\"This Place Is Death\">{{cite episode |credits=[[Edward Kitsis|Kitsis, Edward]] (writer), [[Adam Horowitz (screenwriter)|Horowitz, Adam]] (writer), [[Paul A. Edwards|Edwards, Paul]] (director) |title=[[This Place Is Death]] |series=[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]] |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |season=5 |number=5 |airdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> The character of Charlotte is written out in the fifth episode of the season,<ref name=\"This Place Is Death\"/> as well as Faraday in the fourteenth and overall one hundredth episode.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=[[The Variable]] |series=[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]] |credits=[[Edward Kitsis|Kitsis, Edward]] (writer), [[Adam Horowitz (screenwriter)|Horowitz, Adam]] (writer), [[Paul A. Edwards|Edwards, Paul]] (director) |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |airdate=April 29, 2009 |season=5 |number=14}}</ref>\n\nThose who previously received star billing in season four, but did not in season five include [[Claire Littleton]] ([[Emilie de Ravin]]), who followed an apparition of her deceased father into the forest and later appeared in Jacob's cabin and [[Michael Dawson (Lost)|Michael Dawson]] ([[Harold Perrineau]]), who died when the freighter exploded.<ref>{{cite episode |credits=[[Edward Kitsis|Kitsis, Edward]] (writer), [[Adam Horowitz (screenwriter)|Adam Horowitz]] (writer), [[Stephen Williams (director)|Williams, Stephen]] (director) |title=[[Something Nice Back Home]] |series=[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]] |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |season=4 |number=10 |airdate=May 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |credits=[[Elizabeth Sarnoff|Sarnoff, Elizabeth]] (writer), [[Kyle Pennington|Pennington, Kyle]] (writer), [[Paul A. Edwards|Edwards, Paul]] (director) |title=[[Cabin Fever (Lost)|Cabin Fever]] |series=[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]] |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |season=4 |number=11 |airdate=May 8, 2008}}</ref><ref name=HPinterview>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/lost-harold-perrineau-36053.aspx |title=Harold Perrineau Dishes on His ''Lost'' Exit (Again) |work=[[TV Guide]] |author=Malcolm, Shawna |date=May 30, 2008 |accessdate=December 1, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122081721/http://www.tvguide.com/news/lost-harold-perrineau-36053.aspx |archivedate=January 22, 2009 }}</ref> Emilie de Ravin returned as a regular cast member in season six.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dos Santos, Kristin |date=June 2, 2008 |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/8946/spoiler-chat-30-rock-lost-gossip-girl |title=Spoiler Chat: ''30 Rock'', ''Lost'', ''Gossip Girl'' |publisher=[[E! Online]] |accessdate=August 30, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929065333/http://www.eonline.com/news/8946/spoiler-chat-30-rock-lost-gossip-girl |archivedate=September 29, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=LATimes>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/11/entertainment/ca-lost11 |title=Spring TV Previews: ''Lost'' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |author=Fernandez, Maria Elena |date=January 11, 2009 |accessdate=January 11, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312095843/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/11/entertainment/ca-lost11 |archivedate=March 12, 2009 }}</ref> Furthermore, former main cast member [[Malcolm David Kelley]], who portrays [[Walt Lloyd]], Michael's son, makes guest appearances in the fifth season.<ref name=LATimes/> Second season main cast member [[Michelle Rodriguez]] portrays the deceased [[Ana Lucia Cortez]] in one episode.<ref name=\"premier\"/>\n\n[[File:LostS5Cast.jpg|thumb|right|400px|From left to right: [[Ben Linus|Ben]], [[Desmond Hume|Desmond]], [[Hugo \"Hurley\" Reyes|Hurley]], [[Juliet Burke|Juliet]], [[James \"Sawyer\" Ford|Sawyer]], [[Jack Shephard|Jack]], [[Daniel Faraday|Faraday]], [[Sayid Jarrah|Sayid]], [[Sun-Hwa Kwon|Sun]], [[Kate Austen|Kate]], [[John Locke (Lost)|Locke]], [[Jin-Soo Kwon|Jin]], and [[Miles Straume|Miles]]]]\n\nSeveral of the guest stars from past seasons reprise their roles in season five. [[Nestor Carbonell]] appears as the apparently ageless [[Richard Alpert (Lost)|Richard Alpert]] in nine episodes; [[Cheech Marin]] returns as Hurley's father, David Reyes; [[Fran\u00e7ois Chau]] portrays [[Dharma Initiative]] scientist Dr. Pierre Chang; [[Lance Reddick]] continues to appear as the mysterious Matthew Abaddon; [[Sonya Walger]] plays Desmond's wife, [[Penny Widmore]]; [[William Mapother]] portrays deceased Other [[Ethan Rom]]; [[Jeff Fahey]] returns as pilot [[Frank Lapidus]]; and [[L. Scott Caldwell]] and [[Sam Anderson]] continue to play married couple [[Rose and Bernard Nadler|Rose Henderson]] and [[Bernard Nadler]], respectively.<ref name=premier>{{cite web|url=http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=123108_06 |title=Lost (1/21; Season Premiere) |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Medianet |date=December 31, 2008 |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108004217/http://abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=123108_06 |archivedate=January 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20242405,00.html |title=''Fringe''{{'s}} Lance Reddick: 'Mariah Will Have a Film Career' |author=Sullivan, Emmet |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=November 25, 2008 |accessdate=December 6, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220035249/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20242405%2C00.html |archivedate=December 20, 2008 }}</ref> Recurring guest stars [[Alan Dale]] and [[John Terry (actor)|John Terry]] who play billionaire [[Charles Widmore]] and deceased [[Christian Shephard]], respectively reprise their roles. The character of [[Danielle Rousseau]] is present in the fifth season as a younger version, played by [[Melissa Farman]]. [[Mira Furlan]], who previously portrayed an older Rousseau, asked for her character to be written out of the series because she did not want to travel to Hawaii to film her scenes.<ref name=\"Gloria\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gloria.com.hr/intervju/showpage.php?id=4855 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430135806/http://www.gloria.com.hr/intervju/showpage.php?id=4855 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 30, 2008 |title=GORAN GAJIC / Vratila se roda |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |last=Rodic |first=Jasmina |date=April 28, 2008 |work=[[Gloria (magazine)|Gloria]] |language=Croatian }}</ref> [[Tania Raymonde]] returns as her daughter, [[Alex (Lost)|Alex]]. [[Fionnula Flanagan]] also returns as Eloise Hawking. [[Patrick Fischler]] plays Phil, a member of the [[DHARMA Initiative]]. [[Brad William Henke]] portrays Bram, a survivor of Ajira Airways flight 316. [[Sterling Beaumon]] reprises his role of young Ben for four episodes in the second half of the season. [[Marsha Thomason]] also returns briefly as [[Naomi Dorrit]]. The final recurring character is Vincent, Walt's yellow lab. The producers stated that Vincent survives to the series' conclusion.<ref name=\"comic\">{{cite podcast|host=[[Damon Lindelof|Lindelof, Damon]], [[Carlton Cuse|Cuse, Carlton]], [[Matthew Fox (actor)|Fox, Matthew]] |date=August 1, 2008 |url=http://ll.media.abc.com/podcast/audio/itunes/LOST_2008%20ComicCon_audio_podcast_43d56421-8030-48a4-a2ef-75de6920e61c_1749705.mp3 |title=Comic-Con International |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC.com]] |accessdate=August 28, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220143659/http://ll.media.abc.com/podcast/audio/itunes/LOST_2008%20ComicCon_audio_podcast_43d56421-8030-48a4-a2ef-75de6920e61c_1749705.mp3 |archivedate=December 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral new recurring characters are introduced in the fifth season. Two characters introduced in the premiere are Lara, Dr. Chang's wife and Miles' mother, who is portrayed by Leslie Ishii, and Dan Norton, an attorney who is given the task of performing a maternity test on Kate and Aaron, portrayed by [[Tom Irwin (actor)|Tom Irwin]].<ref name=premier/><ref>{{cite web|author=Ausiello, Michael |date=August 19, 2008 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/08/20/ask-ausiello-2-10/ |title=Spoilers on ''Lost'', ''Grey's'', ''Dexter'', ''Smallville'', ''Gossip Girl'', and More! |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=August 28, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815220709/http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/08/20/ask-ausiello-2-10/ |archivedate=August 15, 2011 }}</ref> Another pair of recurring characters, Caesar played by [[Sa\u00efd Taghmaoui]] and Ilana, played by [[Zuleikha Robinson]], are introduced in the sixth episode, \"[[316 (Lost)|316]]\". Ilana was upgraded to the main cast in the sixth season. [[Reiko Aylesworth]] guest-stars in three episodes as Amy, a member of the [[Dharma Initiative]], a scientific group that did research on the island in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/11/16/lost-scoop-myst/ |title=''Lost'' Scoop: Mystery Gal's Secret Revealed! |author=Ausiello, Michael |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=November 16, 2008 |accessdate=November 18, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908130051/http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/11/16/lost-scoop-myst/ |archivedate=September 8, 2012 }}</ref> Eric Lange portrays Radzinsky, a member of the Dharma Initiative, in seven episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cincinnati.com/article/20090318/ENT/903180346 |title=Actor finally found ''Lost'' |author=Kiesewetter, John |work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=March 18, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321065441/http://news.cincinnati.com/article/20090318/ENT/903180346 |archivedate=March 21, 2009 }}</ref> Two new recurring characters appeared in the fifth-season finale: Jacob, the well-known and unseen leader of [[the Others (Lost)|the Others]], played by [[Mark Pellegrino]], and his unnamed nemesis (nicknamed \"Samuel\" in the casting call), whom Ausiello likened to [[J. R. Ewing]] and is portrayed by [[Titus Welliver]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/02/26/ask-ausiello-3-4/ |title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on ''House'', ''Daisies'', ''Damages'', ''Smallville'', ''24'', ''Burn Notice'', ''NCIS'', ''Prison Break'', ''CSI'', ''ER'', ''Dollhouse'', ''30 Rock'', ''Lost'', and more! |author=Ausiello, Michael |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=February 25, 2009 |accessdate=February 26, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106042748/http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/02/26/ask-ausiello-3-4/ |archivedate=January 6, 2012 }}</ref> [[Sean Whalen]], who previously portrayed Neil Frogurt in the ''[[Lost: Missing Pieces]]'' [[mobisodes]], reprised his role in the first two episodes of season five.<ref name=premier/>\n\n==Reception==\nSeason 5 received mostly positive critical reception. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the season has an 88% approval rating, with average rating of 8.9/10, based on 17 reviews. The website's consensus reads, \"Though it introduces yet more unanswered questions, Season 5 of ''Lost'' also moves quickly, covers more character development, and fleshes out its rich world further for hungry fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lost: Season 5 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lost/s05/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=June 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425150149/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lost/s05 |archivedate=April 25, 2016 }}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the season a score of 78 out of 100 based on 17 reviews, making it generally favorable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/lost/season-5 |title=''Lost'': Season 5 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 20, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815104627/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/lost/season-5 |archivedate=August 15, 2010 }}</ref> Season 5 continued ''Lost''{{'s}} decline in ratings, with the two-hour season premiere being watched by 11.37 million American viewers; the lowest season premiere in the series' history.<ref name=\"premiereratings\"/> Overall, the entire season averaged 11.05 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052709_07 |title=Season Program Rankings from 09/22/08 through 05/27/09 |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Medianet |date=May 27, 2009 |accessdate=September 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531103511/http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052709_07 |archivedate=May 31, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe season was also nominated for five [[Primetime Emmy Awards]], including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series]] for [[Carlton Cuse]] and [[Damon Lindelof]] for the episode \"[[The Incident (Lost)|The Incident]]\", [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] for [[Michael Emerson]], Outstanding Single Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series, and Outstanding Sound Mixing for a Comedy or Drama Series (One Hour).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/lost |title=Lost |publisher=Emmys.com |accessdate=June 7, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928085415/http://www.emmys.com/shows/lost |archivedate=September 28, 2012 }}</ref> The only winner among the nominees was Emerson, after being nominated for the same award two years previous.<ref>{{cite news|author=Eng, Joyce |title=''30 Rock'', ''Mad Men'' Repeat, While Jon Cryer and Toni Collette Surprise at Emmys |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Kristin-Chenoweth-Jon-1009931.aspx |work=TV Guide |date=September 20, 2009 |accessdate=September 20, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5k5m9ucWo?url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Kristin-Chenoweth-Jon-1009931.aspx |archivedate=September 27, 2009 }}</ref> Emerson was later nominated at the [[67th Golden Globe Awards]] for Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role in a Series, Mini-Series or Motion Picture Made for Television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/film/26051 |title=Lost |publisher=GoldenGlobes.org |accessdate=July 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014064202/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/film/26051 |archivedate=October 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{see also|List of Lost episodes}}\nThe number in the \"No. in series\" column refers to the episode's number within the overall series, whereas the number in the \"No. in season\" column refers to the episode's number within this particular season. \"U.S. viewers (million)\" refers to the number of Americans in millions who watched the episode as it was aired. \"Lost: Destiny Calls\", a [[clip-show]] recapping the first four seasons preceded the premiere.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://weblogs.variety.com/on_the_air/2008/11/lost-the-isle-o.html |title=''Lost'': The isle of mystery returns Jan. 21 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |author=Littleton, Cynthia |date=November 7, 2008 |accessdate=November 13, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205120204/http://weblogs.variety.com/on_the_air/2008/11/lost-the-isle-o.html |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref> A second clip show, \"Lost: The Story of the Oceanic 6\", aired on April 22, 2009 (before the 14th episode of the season, which is the 100th episode of the whole series),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20090406abc09/|title=The Story of the Oceanic 6|publisher=The Futon Critic|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref> and a third, \"Lost: A Journey in Time\", was aired before the finale on May 13, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20090427abc06/|title=A Journey in Time|publisher=The Futon Critic|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref>\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table |background=#69D0E3 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=19 |director=11 |writer=25 |aux2=14 |airdate=11 |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |aux2T=Featured character(s) |episodes=\n{{Episode list/sublist|Lost (season 5)\n |EpisodeNumber=87\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=[[Because You Left]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2009|1|21}}\n |DirectedBy=[[Stephen Williams (director)|Stephen Williams]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Damon Lindelof]] & [[Carlton Cuse]]\n |Aux2=''none''\n |Viewers=11.66<ref name=\"premiereratings\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/01/22/wednesday-ratings-lie-to-me-outduels-lost/11338/ |title=Updated Wednesday Ratings: Lie to Me outduels LOST |publisher=TV by the Numbers |author=Gorman, Bill |date=January 22, 2009 |accessdate=October 28, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008230149/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/01/22/wednesday-ratings-lie-to-me-outduels-lost/11338/ |archivedate=October 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=The remaining survivors begin to erratically jump through time after the island is moved. Jack and Ben begin their quest to reunite the Oceanic Six. Hurley and Sayid are ambushed at their safehouse. Kate and Aaron flee their house, after being ordered to submit to a maternity test by two lawyers. Sun has an interesting conversation with Mr. Widmore.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Lost (season 5)\n |EpisodeNumber=88\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=[[The Lie (Lost)|The Lie]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2009|1|21}}\n |DirectedBy=[[Jack Bender]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Edward Kitsis]] & [[Adam Horowitz (screenwriter)|Adam Horowitz]]\n |Aux2=[[Hugo \"Hurley\" Reyes|Hurley]]\n |Viewers=11.08<ref name=\"premiereratings\"/>\n |ShortSummary=Hurley and Sayid are on the run from the police. Hurley confesses to his mother that the Oceanic Six have been lying. The island survivors are attacked by armed men. Ben learns that he only has seventy hours to reunite the Oceanic Six and return them to the island.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Lost (season 5)\n |EpisodeNumber=89\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=[[Jughead (Lost)|Jughead]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2009|1|28}}\n |DirectedBy=[[Rod Holcomb]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Elizabeth Sarnoff]] & [[Paul Zbyszewski]]\n |Aux2=[[Desmond Hume|Desmond]]\n |Viewers=11.07<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/01/29/wednesday-ratings-cbs-news-with-katie-couriclost/11710/ |title=Wednesday Ratings: CBS News with Katie Couric...LOST! |publisher=TV by the Numbers |author=Seidman, Robert |date=January 29, 2009 |accessdate=October 28, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008222921/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/01/29/wednesday-ratings-cbs-news-with-katie-couriclost/11710/ |archivedate=October 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Desmond goes in search of Daniel Faraday's mother and learns from Charles Widmore that she is in Los Angeles. The island survivors jump to 1954, where Locke is unable to convince Alpert he is from the future and Faraday is given the task of defusing a hydrogen bomb.\n |LineColor= 69D0E3\n }}